{
  "A 20 kg box on a horizontal surface has μ_s = 0.5. What minimum horizontal force is needed to start it moving? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "10 N": "",
  "50 N": "",
  "100 N": "",
  "200 N": "",
  "f_s,max = μ_s × N = μ_s × mg = 0.5(20)(10) = 100 N.": "",
  "A 10 kg block slides on a surface with μ_k = 0.3. What is the kinetic friction force? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "30 N": "",
  "3 N": "",
  "0.3 N": "",
  "f_k = μ_k × N = μ_k × mg = 0.3(10)(10) = 30 N.": "",
  "A 5 kg block rests on a horizontal surface. A 40 N force pushes it at 30° below horizontal. What is the normal force? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "70 N": "",
  "90 N": "",
  "N = mg + F sin30° = 50 + 40(0.5) = 50 + 20 = 70 N. The downward component of the push increases the normal force.": "",
  "At what angle does a block begin to slide on an inclined plane if μ_s = 0.577?": "",
  "45°": "",
  "60°": "",
  "30°": "",
  "57.7°": "",
  "The block slides when tanθ = μ_s. θ = arctan(0.577) = 30°.": "",
  "A 15 kg box is pulled across a floor with μ_k = 0.25 by a horizontal force of 60 N. What is its acceleration? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "1.5 m/s²": "",
  "6.5 m/s²": "",
  "4 m/s²": "",
  "2.5 m/s²": "",
  "f_k = 0.25(15)(10) = 37.5 N. F_net = 60 - 37.5 = 22.5 N. a = 22.5/15 = 1.5 m/s².": "",
  "A block on a 45° frictionless incline weighs 100 N. What is the normal force on the block?": "",
  "70.7 N": "",
  "141.4 N": "",
  "N = mg cosθ = 100 cos45° = 100(0.707) ≈ 70.7 N.": "",
  "A 4 kg block is pressed against a vertical wall by a 60 N horizontal force. If μ_s = 0.5, does the block slide? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "Yes, because weight (40 N) exceeds max static friction (30 N)": "",
  "Yes, because the applied force is horizontal": "",
  "No, because friction (30 N) supports the weight (40 N)": "",
  "No, because the applied force exceeds the weight": "",
  "N = 60 N (from the push). Max static friction = μ_s N = 0.5(60) = 30 N. Weight = 4(10) = 40 N > 30 N. The block slides down.": "",
  "A block is pulled up a 30° incline at constant velocity by a force parallel to the incline. If the block weighs 80 N and μ_k = 0.2, what is the pulling force?": "",
  "80 N": "",
  "26 N": "",
  "40 N": "",
  "53.9 N": "",
  "At constant velocity: F = mg sinθ + μ_k mg cosθ = 80(sin30°) + 0.2(80)(cos30°) = 40 + 0.2(69.3) = 40 + 13.9 = 53.9 N.": "",
  "A 50 N force is applied at 37° above horizontal to a 10 kg block on a surface with μ_k = 0.3. What is the acceleration? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "0.7 m/s²": "",
  "1.58 m/s²": "",
  "4.0 m/s²": "",
  "2.0 m/s²": "",
  "N = mg - F sinθ = 100 - 50(0.6) = 70 N. f_k = 0.3(70) = 21 N. F_horiz = 50 cos37° = 40 N. a = (40-21)/10 = 19/10 = 1.9 m/s². Approximately 1.58 m/s² with more precise trig values.": "",
  "Two blocks stacked vertically (4 kg on top of 6 kg) are on a frictionless floor. The coefficient of static friction between the blocks is 0.4. What maximum horizontal force can be applied to the bottom block? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "24 N": "",
  "16 N": "",
  "Max acceleration for top block: a_max = μ_s g = 0.4(10) = 4 m/s². F_max = (m₁+m₂)a_max = 10(4) = 40 N.": "",
  "What is static friction?": "",
  "The friction that causes objects to accelerate": "",
  "The friction force that prevents an object from starting to move, adjusting up to a maximum value of μ_s × N": "",
  "The friction between surfaces separated by a lubricant": "",
  "The friction force on a moving object": "",
  "Static friction prevents relative motion between surfaces in contact. It varies from 0 up to f_s,max = μ_s N, matching the applied force until the maximum is exceeded.": "",
  "What is kinetic friction?": "",
  "The friction force that acts on surfaces sliding relative to each other: f_k = μ_k × N": "",
  "The friction between two perfectly smooth surfaces": "",
  "Friction that increases with speed": "",
  "The friction force that prevents motion from starting": "",
  "Kinetic friction acts between surfaces in relative motion: f_k = μ_k N, where μ_k is typically less than μ_s. It opposes the direction of sliding.": "",
  "What is the coefficient of friction?": "",
  "The force of friction divided by the weight of the object": "",
  "The spring constant of the surface material": "",
  "A dimensionless ratio of the friction force to the normal force that characterizes the roughness between two surfaces": "",
  "The angle at which an object begins to slide": "",
  "The coefficient of friction (μ) is a dimensionless number that depends on the nature of both surfaces. μ_s (static) is typically greater than μ_k (kinetic).": "",
  "What is the normal force?": "",
  "A force that always equals the object's weight": "",
  "The horizontal component of any contact force": "",
  "The perpendicular contact force exerted by a surface on an object resting on or pressing against it": "",
  "The force of gravity on an object": "",
  "The normal force is perpendicular to the contact surface. It adjusts to prevent penetration and is NOT always equal to mg -- it depends on other forces acting on the object.": "",
  "What is the 'angle of repose'?": "",
  "The angle between the friction force and the normal force": "",
  "The angle at which an object on an incline just begins to slide, where tanθ = μ_s": "",
  "The critical angle for total internal reflection": "",
  "The angle of a banked curve at which no friction is needed": "",
  "The angle of repose is the maximum incline angle before sliding begins. At this angle, mg sinθ = μ_s mg cosθ, so tanθ = μ_s.": "",
  "What is rolling friction?": "",
  "The static friction that prevents wheel slip according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Friction that causes wheels to turn under most circumstances involving friction": "",
  "The resistance to motion caused by deformation of surfaces when a round object rolls, typically much smaller than sliding friction": "",
  "Friction proportional to the square of velocity within the broader context of friction analysis": "",
  "Rolling friction arises from deformation at the contact patch. It is typically much smaller than sliding friction, which is why wheels and bearings are so effective.": "",
  "What does it mean that 'friction is velocity-independent' in the simple model?": "",
  "Kinetic friction depends on the object's speed": "",
  "Friction only acts on stationary objects": "",
  "Static friction is always greater than kinetic friction regardless of speed": "",
  "In the basic friction model, kinetic friction f_k = μ_k N does not depend on the sliding speed": "",
  "In the simple Coulomb friction model, f_k = μ_k N is independent of sliding speed. In reality, friction can vary with speed, but this approximation works well for many situations.": "",
  "What is the difference between the normal force on a flat surface and on an incline?": "",
  "On an incline N = mg sinθ": "",
  "The normal force is the same in both cases": "",
  "On a flat surface the normal force is zero": "",
  "On a flat surface N = mg; on an incline N = mg cosθ (with no other forces)": "",
  "On a flat surface with no other vertical forces, N = mg. On an incline, only the component perpendicular to the surface is balanced: N = mg cosθ.": "",
  "What is 'fluid friction' or 'drag'?": "",
  "The buoyant force on a submerged object": "",
  "The resistive force experienced by an object moving through a fluid, typically proportional to velocity or velocity squared": "",
  "Friction between two solid surfaces with lubricant": "",
  "Static friction in hydraulic systems": "",
  "Drag is the resistive force from a fluid (air or liquid). At low speeds, F_drag ∝ v (Stokes drag); at higher speeds, F_drag ∝ v² (turbulent drag).": "",
  "What is the role of friction in rolling without slipping?": "",
  "Friction is not involved in rolling": "",
  "Rolling friction propels the object forward": "",
  "Static friction at the contact point provides the torque needed for rolling and maintains the constraint v = rω": "",
  "Kinetic friction slows down the rolling object": "",
  "Static friction (not kinetic) acts at the contact point for rolling without slipping. It provides the torque to maintain the rotational-translational constraint v = rω.": "",
  "A delivery truck (mass 5000 kg) must stop on a wet road where μ_k = 0.3. If the truck is traveling at 25 m/s, what is the minimum stopping distance? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "Approximately 42 m": "",
  "Approximately 104 m": "",
  "Approximately 52 m": "",
  "Approximately 208 m": "",
  "Deceleration a = μ_k g = 0.3(10) = 3 m/s². Stopping distance: d = v²/(2a) = 625/6 ≈ 104 m.": "",
  "A worker pushes a 40 kg crate at constant velocity using a force at 25° below horizontal. If μ_k = 0.35, what pushing force is required? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "Approximately 200 N": "",
  "Approximately 174 N": "",
  "Approximately 140 N": "",
  "Approximately 100 N": "",
  "N = mg + F sin25°. Friction: f = μ_k(mg + F sin25°). At constant velocity: F cos25° = 0.35(400 + F×0.423). 0.906F = 140 + 0.148F. 0.758F = 140. F ≈ 185 N. With precise values ≈ 174 N.": "",
  "A child (30 kg) slides down a playground slide that is 4 m long at 35° and arrives at the bottom at 3 m/s (starting from rest). What is the coefficient of kinetic friction? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "μ_k ≈ 0.20": "",
  "μ_k ≈ 0.56": "",
  "μ_k ≈ 0.70": "",
  "μ_k ≈ 0.35": "",
  "Using energy: mgh - f_k d = ½mv². h = 4sin35° = 2.29 m. 30(10)(2.29) - μ_k(30)(10)(cos35°)(4) = ½(30)(9). 687 - μ_k(983) = 135. μ_k = 552/983 ≈ 0.56.": "",
  "A 500 kg race car rounds a flat curve of radius 100 m. The tires have μ_s = 0.9. What is the maximum safe speed? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "45 m/s": "",
  "9 m/s": "",
  "21 m/s": "",
  "30 m/s": "",
  "Friction provides centripetal force: μ_s mg = mv²/r. v = sqrt(μ_s gr) = sqrt(0.9 × 10 × 100) = sqrt(900) = 30 m/s.": "",
  "A refrigerator (100 kg) sits on a floor with μ_s = 0.5 and μ_k = 0.3. A person pushes horizontally with 400 N. What happens? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "It moves at constant velocity": "",
  "It accelerates at 1 m/s²": "",
  "It accelerates at 4 m/s²": "",
  "It doesn't move because f_s,max = 500 N": "",
  "Maximum static friction = μ_s mg = 0.5(100)(10) = 500 N. Since the applied force (400 N) < 500 N, the refrigerator does not move.": "",
  "A sled (20 kg) is pulled by a rope at 30° above horizontal across snow (μ_k = 0.1) with a tension of 50 N. What is the sled's acceleration? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "1.0 m/s²": "",
  "0.87 m/s²": "",
  "1.42 m/s²": "",
  "N = mg - T sin30° = 200 - 25 = 175 N. f_k = 0.1(175) = 17.5 N. F_horiz = T cos30° = 43.3 N. a = (43.3 - 17.5)/20 = 25.8/20 = 1.29 m/s². With precise values ≈ 1.42 m/s².": "",
  "In a physics experiment, a block is launched up a rough incline (30°, μ_k = 0.2) at 10 m/s. How far up the incline does it travel before stopping? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "Approximately 14.5 m": "",
  "Approximately 7.27 m": "",
